% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Marijuana Legalization
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro82).  % [pro] But with legalization, proper means to settle disputes would be created.
arg(pro15).  % [pro] 27% of supporters say legalization would lead to improved regulation of marijuana.
arg(pro15b).  % [pro] 27% of supporters say legalization would lead to increased tax revenues.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] The paper of record is continuing to make the case for legalization over a series of editorials.
arg(pro4b).  % [pro] The paper of record addresses the social costs of cannabis prohibition.
arg(pro4c).  % [pro] The paper of record addresses the racist history of cannabis prohibition.
arg(pro4d).  % [pro] The paper of record addresses the wasted resources of cannabis prohibition.
arg(pro95).  % [pro] Marijuana also helps medical conditions as a more natural substitute to pharmaceuticals.
arg(pro36).  % [pro] Teen marijuana use has fallen slightly over the past five years.
arg(pro36b).  % [pro] Four states and the District of Columbia have legalized marijuana and 23 other states allow medical use.
arg(pro32).  % [pro] Though more adults are smoking pot, the MTF data suggests that teens aren't following suit.
arg(pro29).  % [pro] It is believed that legalizing recreational weed will cut off a revenue stream for illegal drug traders.
arg(con18).  % [con] So, there’s a good reason most habitual marijuana users come off as stupid.
arg(con95).  % [con] The study found that even those who quit in adulthood were not able to recover the lost IQ points.
arg(con14).  % [con] Any time marijuana use is made legal, drug accessibility to children will increase.
arg(con87).  % [con] Marijuana tends to be a starter drug for people who move on to heavier duty drugs, sometimes legal and sometimes illegal.
arg(con87b).  % [con] We do not want marijuana in our society because it is a heathenistic activity.
arg(con87c).  % [con] Society is changing rapidly to a different type of society, and nobody is getting a chance to discuss it.
arg(con115).  % [con] Marijuana legalization has been bad for the whole Pueblo community.
arg(con70).  % [con] Marijuana is even more toxic than cigarette smoke.
arg(con12).  % [con] Marijuana is terrible for your physical health

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con14, pro15).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Con14 challenges the premise that legalization improves regulation by asserting it would increase child accessibility.
att(con115, pro4b).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — B asserts legalization is harmful, which conflicts with A’s implication that prohibition’s social costs make legalization preferable.
att(pro4d, con115).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — A claims prohibition wastes resources (implying legalization is preferable), while B asserts legalization is harmful, presenting mutually exclusive policy conclusions.
att(con70, pro4d).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B claims marijuana is more toxic, challenging the premise that prohibition wastes resources by suggesting the policy is justified for health reasons.
att(con12, pro4d).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B asserts marijuana is terrible for health, undermining A's premise that prohibition is merely a waste of resources.
att(con95, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B presents evidence of irreversible IQ loss, challenging the premise that marijuana is a safe medical alternative.
att(pro95, con87b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — A argues marijuana should be used for health reasons, implying acceptance, while B argues it should be rejected on cultural grounds, making the conclusions mutually exclusive.
att(pro95, con115).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — A presents marijuana as medically beneficial, whereas B claims legalization harms the Pueblo community, yielding opposite conclusions about its overall impact.
att(pro95, con70).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — A says marijuana is a natural medical substitute, while B claims it is more toxic than cigarettes, directly opposing the health assessment.
att(pro95, con12).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — A’s claim of medical benefit conflicts with B’s assertion that marijuana is terrible for physical health, making the conclusions incompatible.
att(pro4b, con115).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — [symmetric rebuttal] B asserts legalization is harmful, which conflicts with A’s implication that prohibition’s social costs make legalization preferable.
att(con115, pro4d).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — [symmetric rebuttal] A claims prohibition wastes resources (implying legalization is preferable), while B asserts legalization is harmful, presenting mutually exclusive policy conclusions.
